 ‘ought’: the predictive ‘ought’ is basic, and is interpreted in terms of probability. Instrumental ‘oughts’ are analyzed as predictive ‘oughts’ occurring under an ‘in order that’ modifer (the end-relational theory). The theory is then extended to categorical uses of ‘ought’: it is argued that they are special rhetorical uses of the instrumental ‘ought’. Plausible conversational principles explain how this end-relational ‘ought’ can perform the expressive functions of the moral ‘ought’. The notion of an ‘ought-simpliciter’ is also discussed.","topics":["ethics","mind"],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s11098-008-9202-8"},{"doi":"10.1007/s11098-008-9203-7","title":"Contextualism, relativism and ordinary speakers’ judgments","authors":["Martin Montminy"],"journal":"phil-studies","published":"2008-02-01","volume":"143","issue":"3","pages":"341-356","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s11098-008-9203-7"},{"doi":"10.1007/s11098-007-9197-6","title":"Summation relations and portions of stuff","authors":["Maureen Donnelly","Thomas Bittner"],"journal":"phil-studies","published":"2008-02-01","volume":"143","issue":"2","pages":"167-185","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s11098-007-9197-6"},{"doi":"10.1007/s11098-008-9200-x","title":"Means-end coherence, stringency, and subjective reasons","authors":["Mark Schroeder"],"journal":"phil-studies","published":"2008-02-01","volume":"143","issue":"2","pages":"223-248","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s11098-008-9200-x"},{"doi":"10.1007/s11098-007-9194-9","title":"Naturalism, fallibilism, and the a priori","authors":["Lisa Warenski"],"journal":"phil-studies","published":"2008-01-30","volume":"142","issue":"3","pages":"403-426","abstract":"","topics":[],"si":null,"url":"https://doi.org/10.1007/s11098-007-9194-9"},{"doi":"10.1007/s11098-007-9193-x","title":"The folk on knowing how","authors":["John Bengson","Marc A. Moffett","Jennife